  "report": {
    "sections": {
      "What we found": "The estimate that stands out most is the chance of a prolonged stay during this hospital admission, put at about 80% by a model we consider reliable (though its confidence here is moderate). The model also estimates a roughly 4-in-10 chance of not surviving the next 12 months \u2014 this comes from a reliable model, but its confidence is lower, so please treat that particular figure with extra caution. Alongside these, the profile points to a very high likelihood of long-standing high blood pressure and high cholesterol, and a higher-than-usual likelihood of cardiovascular disease. Looking directly at your recorded values, a few things catch the eye: your albumin is low at 2.7, your diastolic blood pressure and mean arterial pressure ran low across readings (diastolic as low as 38, mean arterial pressure around 51\u201360), and your hemoglobin is mildly low at 11.3. All of these are model estimates and recorded measurements, not confirmed diagnoses.",
      "What may be contributing": "Several of these threads connect. A low albumin often reflects overall nutritional or general health reserve, and it shows up as a driver in both the longer-stay and the one-year outlook estimates \u2014 the same low reading the model leaned on. Your age and liver-related labs (albumin, ALT) also feed the longer-term estimate. The blood pressure pattern is worth noting on its own: the consistently low diastolic and mean arterial pressures, paired with a heart rate at the upper-normal end, form a picture the model links to how your admission may unfold. Body temperature and oxygen levels, which the length-of-stay model highlighted, were actually in normal ranges in your recorded snapshot. These are associations the model has drawn, not proven causes.",
      "What this means": "The strongest signal is that your care team may reasonably expect this admission to run longer than average \u2014 that estimate rests on a reliable model. The longer-term survival estimate deserves a more measured reading: it comes from a reliable model but with lower confidence, so it is better seen as one input for conversation than a firm prediction. The chronic-condition likelihoods for blood pressure and cholesterol are high and consistent. The readmission and exact length-of-stay figures come from models flagged as weak, so they carry the least weight and shouldn't drive any conclusions.",
      "What to do next": "These results are best reviewed with the clinicians who know your full history. It may help to ask them about the low albumin and mild anemia, and about the low blood pressure readings \u2014 whether they reflect anything that needs closer monitoring or support. Because several estimates hinge on nutrition and overall reserve, a conversation about that side of your recovery could be worthwhile. Bring any questions about the longer-term outlook openly; a clinician can put it in the context of your real, day-to-day condition rather than a single percentage.",
      "When to seek care urgently": "Seek urgent attention for symptoms such as chest pain or pressure, sudden shortness of breath, fainting or near-fainting, confusion or difficulty staying awake, signs of a serious infection like high fever or shaking chills, or any sudden weakness, difficulty speaking, or one-sided numbness. In a hospital setting, tell staff right away if you feel lightheaded, unusually weak, or that something is suddenly wrong."
    },
    "disclaimer": "This summary is generated by a computer model to help you understand your health information. It is not a diagnosis and not a substitute for advice from a qualified clinician. Always talk to your healthcare provider about your results and any decisions."
